<h1>Tutorial 7. Pressing. Sewing Tunnels for Plastic Bones.</h1>
<h2>Inserting Bones in the Tunnels.</h2>
<p><strong>I need to press the garment again.</strong> I flatten the top edge of the bodice by pressing it on a cup pressing mould.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I hope you have noticed that there are hardly any bumps where the princess seams meet along the top edge of the bodice. </strong>It is because I carefully notched out all excess thickness in the seams.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And now I want your attention please! There is a simple but very useful trick! I pin together the princess seams of the face and the lining starting from the centre of the back. </strong></p>
<p>Please note that it is not compulsory to align princess seams strictly, stitch to stitch. They can be slightly shifted against each other as long as the size of the lining fits the size of the face. Make sure to carefully re-distribute all face and lining fabric to eliminate air bubbles. If you notice a considerable difference or mismatch between the face and the lining, you will have to rip it up and even it out.</p>
<p><strong>The princess seams must be pinned together in a fixed order! </strong></p>
<p><strong>You must start from the back and gradually move toward the centre.</strong> I pin together the first pair of princess seams, then turn the bodice around and pin together the symmetric pair of princess seams on the opposite half of it, etc. I keep moving from the centre of the back to the centre of the front.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Here is the last unpinned princess seam </strong>which will show whether the size of the lining matches the size of the face perfectly or not:</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Everything does match well! There are no air bubbles!&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>Next, <strong>I measure the distance from the bottom edge of the bodice to the supposed under-bust line up along the bust princess seam </strong>and mark a point at the end. And I mark a symmetric point on the other bust princess seam.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And I sew over the underside of the lacing edges with sewn-in bones. </strong>I simply sew right over the seams holding the bones. The stitches form two tunnels where I will later insert plastic bones. If you prefer steel spiral bones, you can use them instead.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Look what I do next. I sew right over the groove of the princess seam at the back of the bodice: </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And I make another row of parallel stitches at about 1-1.2cm from the previous one:&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I check whether the tunnel is wide enough to fit a plastic bone.&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>The bone fits in well so I will keep the same width for the rest of the tunnels.</p>
<p>I keep moving further from the back and closer to the centre. <strong>I sew right over the groove of the side princess seam. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>And I sew a parallel row to form a tunnel with the same width as the first one.</strong> If you don't trust your eyes, just mark corresponding lines with a disappearing ink pen or a piece of soap.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I make the same kind of a tunnel at the intermediate front princess seam. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Now the bust princess seam: </strong>I sew over the groove of the princess seam, stop at the mark I made, turn the garment on the needle, make a couple of stitches to achieve the desired width, and sew another vertical row of parallel stitches down to the bottom of the garment. <strong>The result is a short tunnel which stops at the under-bust line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I do the same with the other bust princess seam.&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><strong>And I continue in the same manner to the very end of the bodice. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Now I need to insert plastic bones into the tunnels.</strong> I secure the bottom edge of the bodice with pins just in case. <strong>The bone is supposed to be 1.5-2cm shorter than the tunnel.</strong> I cut bones of equal lengths in pairs to insert them into symmetric tunnels from either side of the bodice. I slightly even out the ends and make them round. I don't think it is necessary to file them smooth. I won't do this. It is enough to just trim the sharp corners.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I push the bones in the tunnels with the help of a screwdriver: </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>I keep folding the bottom edge of the bodice to make sure the bones won't get in the way later when I finish the hem. I cut bones in pairs to keep them at the same lengths on both halves of the bodice.</p>
<p>People often ask me whether it is okay to use plastic boning sold by the roll or by the meter. It all depends on the manufacturer and on their density. In my opinion, such boning is only suitable for children's clothes because it is very soft. Pre-cut bones are stiffer, more durable, and harder to break. It is your own choice in the end. <strong>Sew a pilot sample: </strong>if you don't like it, you will look for a different solution or use steel spiral bones. Steel spiral bones have their own pros and cons. For example, you need to have a special tool for capping their ends. Steel spirals are also heavier and may get rusty overtime. Well, and they are not exactly cheap either.</p>
<p><strong>I have inserted all bones in the tunnels. The bodice looks completely different now! </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%207.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
